      <div class="wrap">
       <div class="avatar">

        <a class="gravatar">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f4596eff172e0f64aceb4c6fa26e0cfe?s=64&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D64&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-64 photo' height='64' width='64' />        </a>

       </div>
       <div class="details">
        <p class="head"><span class="info"><a href="#comment-40448">#5</a> written by

                        <b  id="commentauthor-40448">Pelot</b>
		   September 19th, 2013 at 12:23</span></p>
               <div class="text">
								<div id="commentbody-40448"> <p>&#8220;the 64-bit CPU will not change anything from a JavaScript perspective&#8221;. That&#8217;s not quite accurate, given that JavaScriptCore stores JavaScript values (every variable, parameter, etc.) in 64 bits. That&#8217;s kind of a hassle on 32-bit architectures but great for 64-bit architectures because it means the value references can fit into a register.</p>
<p>I suggest to correct that in your article.</p>
 </div>
               </div>
       </div>
